11 Illyricum] the province of Illyricum was entrusted to Caesar along with the two Gauls for five years in 59 ac. In April 56 lac. Caesar was at Luca where he had an interview with Pompey and Crassus, the latter of whom he had previously met at Ravenna. The result of the conference was that Pompey and Crassus were to be nominated consuls for the ensning year and Caesar's command was to be prolonged for another five years. Cf. Plut. Caes. ar; Cic. Ep. Fam. 1. 9; ad Q. Fr. 11. v (Wesenberg); Suet. Caes. 24.

aa Britanniam] there seems to have been a good deal of intercourse between Gaul and Britain in Caesar’s time though the Gauls knew little of the interior of the island. It was visited chiefly by merchants who confined their traffic to the dwellers on the coast: 1V. ao. The Britons usually fumished auxiliaries in the Gallie wars: infra 9, iv. ao. In V1. 13 Caesar tells us that the cultus of the Druids originated in Britain and that those who desired a more accurate acquaintance with its mysteries were in the habit of visiting the island for that purpose.
